      "date": "2011-11-10 17:42:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nIt was decided that no mo invalid jira tickets references to trick the system, so please use some real ticket.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "6be9b7f379b3b84bbd9ebf485f99fa6c7b343268",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-10 18:22:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIt seems like a lot of overhead to open a Jira ticket with the subject \"skip generated files in .gitignore\", with the body \"skip generated files in .gitignore\", and then push a patch, link the change number to the jira ticket, then close the ticket once the change is merged.\n\nI agree as a general rule that changes should have valid Jira tickets, but I think the commit comment in this case fully describes the change that is being made and a Jira ticket is just needless overhead.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
